<p> Many things can make your elbow hurt. A common cause is <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/tendinitis.html">tendinitis</a>, an inflammation or injury to the tendons that attach muscle to bone. Tendinitis of the elbow is a <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/sportsinjuries.html">sports injury</a>, often from playing tennis or golf. You may also get tendinitis from overuse of the elbow.</p>
<p> Other causes of elbow pain include <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/sprainsandstrains.html">sprains and strains</a>, <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/fractures.html">fractures</a> (broken bones), <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/dislocations.html">dislocations</a>, <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/bursitis.html">bursitis</a>, and <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/arthritis.html">arthritis</a>. Treatment depends on the cause.</p> Bones, Joints and Muscles Injuries and Wounds Lesiones y enfermedades del codo Elbow Injuries Tennis Elbow Spanish National Institute of Arthritis and Musculoskeletal and Skin Diseases Hand Injuries and Disorders Wrist Injuries and Disorders Cubital Tunnel Syndrome Tennis Elbow Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Diagnosis and Tests Radiological Society of North America American College of Radiology Video Clinical Trials National Institutes of Health NIH Clinical Trials National Institutes of Health NIH Clinical Trials National Institutes of Health NIH Clinical Trials National Institutes of Health NIH Diagnosis and Tests Radiological Society of North America American College of Radiology Video Specifics American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons Specifics American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Start Here Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Specifics Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research Diagnosis and Tests American Academy of Family Physicians Treatments and Therapies American Academy of Family Physicians Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Find an Expert National Institute of Arthritis and Musculoskeletal and Skin Diseases NIH Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Specifics American Academy of Family Physicians Children Nemours Foundation Journal Articles Specifics National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke NIH Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Specifics Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research Specifics American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons Patient Handouts Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Encyclopedia Medical Encyclopedia Specifics American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons Diagnosis and Tests Nemours Foundation <p>Many older people are victims of elder abuse. It is the mistreatment of an older person, usually by a caregiver. It can happen within the family. It can also happen in assisted living facilities or nursing homes.</p>
<p>The mistreatment may be:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Physical, sexual, or emotional abuse</li>
	<li>Neglect or abandonment</li>
	<li>Financial abuse - stealing of money or belongings</li>
</ul>
<p>Possible signs of elder abuse include unexplained bruises, burns, and injuries. There may also be bed sores and poor hygiene. The person may become withdrawn, agitated, and depressed. There may be a sudden change in the person's financial situation.</p>
<p>Elder abuse will not stop on its own. Someone else needs to step in and help. If you think that an older person is in urgent danger, call 911. Otherwise, contact adult protective services.</p>
